## SOC 2 Implementation Roadmap

### Phase 1: Preparation (Months 1-3)

#### Month 1: Planning and Scoping
- [ ] Define SOC 2 scope (which systems, which TSC)
- [ ] Engage SOC 2 auditor (get recommendations)
- [ ] Establish compliance project team
- [ ] Review current security posture
- [ ] Identify gaps against SOC 2 requirements

#### Month 2: Policy Documentation
- [ ] Document all security policies
- [ ] Create information security policy
- [ ] Create access control policy
- [ ] Create change management policy
- [ ] Create incident response plan
- [ ] Create business continuity plan
- [ ] Create vendor management policy
- [ ] Create data classification policy

#### Month 3: Control Implementation
- [ ] Implement missing security controls
- [ ] Configure audit logging (use this module)
- [ ] Set up access controls (RBAC, MFA)
- [ ] Implement monitoring and alerting
- [ ] Configure encryption (at rest and in transit)
- [ ] Set up backup and disaster recovery
- [ ] Implement vulnerability management

### Phase 2: Readiness Assessment (Month 4)

- [ ] Conduct internal audit (or pre-audit with auditor)
- [ ] Identify remaining gaps
- [ ] Remediate critical findings
- [ ] Test incident response plan
- [ ] Test disaster recovery plan
- [ ] Train staff on policies and procedures
- [ ] Begin collecting evidence

### Phase 3: Observation Period (Months 5-7)

**Type II requires minimum 3 months of continuous control operation**

- [ ] Operate controls consistently
- [ ] Collect audit evidence automatically
- [ ] Perform quarterly access reviews
- [ ] Conduct security awareness training
- [ ] Perform vulnerability scans
- [ ] Review and update policies
- [ ] Monitor for security incidents
- [ ] Document all control activities

**Evidence to Collect:**
- Access logs (automatically via this module)
- Change tickets and approvals
- Training completion records
- Vulnerability scan reports
- Penetration test reports
- Backup verification logs
- Incident records (if any)
- Vendor assessments

### Phase 4: Audit Fieldwork (Months 8-9)

- [ ] Provide evidence to auditor
- [ ] Respond to auditor requests (Information Requests)
- [ ] Conduct management interviews
- [ ] Facilitate system walkthroughs
- [ ] Provide control testing samples
- [ ] Address auditor questions promptly
- [ ] Review draft report
- [ ] Provide management responses (if needed)

### Phase 5: Report and Maintenance (Month 10+)

- [ ] Receive final SOC 2 report
- [ ] Share report with customers (under NDA)
- [ ] Address any exceptions or findings
- [ ] Plan for annual re-attestation
- [ ] Maintain continuous compliance
- [ ] Monitor control effectiveness
- [ ] Update policies as needed

## Key Controls Implementation

### 1. Access Control

**Requirements:**
- Unique user IDs for all users
- Strong password policy (complexity, length, expiration)
- Multi-factor authentication (MFA)
- Role-based access control (RBAC)
- Quarterly access reviews
- Immediate termination of access upon employee exit

**Implementation:**
```typescript
// Example: Enforce MFA at authentication
export async function authenticateUser(credentials: Credentials) {
  const user = await validateCredentials(credentials);

  if (!user.mfaEnabled) {
    throw new Error('MFA is required for all users');
  }

  const mfaValid = await validateMFA(user.id, credentials.mfaToken);
  if (!mfaValid) {
    await logAuthenticationEvent(
      SOC2EventType.LOGIN_FAILED,
      user.id,
      {
        ipAddress: credentials.ipAddress,
        failureReason: 'Invalid MFA token'
      }
    );
    throw new Error('Invalid MFA token');
  }

  await logAuthenticationEvent(
    SOC2EventType.USER_LOGIN,
    user.id,
    {
      ipAddress: credentials.ipAddress,
      mfaUsed: true
    }
  );

  return generateSession(user);
}
```

### 2. Audit Logging

**Requirements:**
- Log all security-relevant events
- Logs protected from modification
- Logs retained for at least 1 year
- Regular log review
- Automated alerting for critical events

**Implementation:**
This module provides comprehensive audit logging. Simply integrate it into your authentication and data access flows.

### 3. Encryption

**Requirements:**
- Encryption at rest for sensitive data
- Encryption in transit (TLS 1.2+)
- Secure key management
- Regular key rotation

**Implementation:**
```typescript
// Example: Enforce TLS and HSTS
export function securityMiddleware() {
  return [
    // Force HTTPS
    (req, res, next) => {
      if (!req.secure && process.env.NODE_ENV === 'production') {
        return res.redirect(`https://${req.headers.host}${req.url}`);
      }
      next();
    },
    // Set security headers
    (req, res, next) => {
      res.setHeader('Strict-Transport-Security', 'max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains');
      res.setHeader('X-Content-Type-Options', 'nosniff');
      res.setHeader('X-Frame-Options', 'DENY');
      res.setHeader('X-XSS-Protection', '1; mode=block');
      next();
    }
  ];
}
```

### 4. Change Management

**Requirements:**
- Documented change management process
- Change approval workflow
- Testing before production deployment
- Rollback procedures
- Emergency change procedures

**Implementation:**
```yaml
# Example: GitHub Actions approval workflow
name: Production Deploy
on:
  push:
    branches: [main]
jobs:
  deploy:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    environment:
      name: production
      # Requires approval from designated reviewers
    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v2
      - name: Deploy to production
        run: |
          # Log change in audit system
          curl -X POST $AUDIT_API/changes \
            -H "Authorization: Bearer $AUDIT_TOKEN" \
            -d '{"change_id":"${{ github.run_id }}","approver":"${{ github.actor }}"}'
          # Deploy
          ./deploy.sh
```

